In TypeScript, you can use conditional types (also known as "type guards") to assert the type of a value based on a condition. This helps the compiler understand that, in practice, the value will conform to a specific type. Here's an example demonstrating how to achieve this:

```typescript
type HasStringOrNumber = x: unknown;
type HasString = x: string & Any;

function processValue(x: HasStringOrNumber): void {
  if (typeof x as string) {
    // x is known to be a string
    console.log('x is a string');
  } else if (typeof x as number) {
    // x is known to be a number
    console.log('x is a number');
  } else {
    // x is neither a string nor a number (e.g., undefined or null)
    console.log('x is neither a string nor a number');
  }
}

processValue(123);  // Output: x is a number
processValue('Hello');  // Output: x is a string
processValue(undefined);  // Output: x is neither a string nor a number
```

This technique can be used to define types based on runtime conditions, making your code more flexible and self-documenting when handling values with multiple possible types.

