A table of contents (TOC) automatically generated in a LaTeX document can be achieved using the `tocloft` package, along with the standard `\tableofcontents` command. Here's an example of how to create a TOC automatically in a LaTeX document:

**Document (main.tex):**

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tocloft}
\renewcommand{\cfttoctitlefont}{\hfill\Large\bfseries}
\setcounter{tocdepth}{3} % Set the depth for ToC (sections up to subsection level)

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents % Include TOC

\section{Introduction}
\subsection{Background}
\subsection{Objectives}

\section{Methods}
\subsection{Data Collection}
\subsection{Data Analysis}

\section{Results}
\subsection{Findings}
\subsection{Discussion}

\section{Conclusion}

\end{document}
```

**Customizing the TOC Appearance (optional):**

To customize the appearance of the TOC, you can modify the options in `tocloft` commands. For example:

```latex
\renewcommand{\cfttoctitlefont}{\hfill\Large\bfseries\color{blue}}
\setcftsecfont{1em\bfseries}
\setcftsubsecfont{1em\itshape}
```

**Compiling and Viewing the Document:**

To compile and view the document, run `pdflatex main.tex` in your LaTeX editor or terminal. The PDF output will include the automatically generated TOC.

Remember to include the necessary packages (`tocloft`, `titlesec`, and `color` for color customization) and adjust the `tocdepth` as needed to control the depth of the ToC hierarchy. This example demonstrates how to create a TOC automatically in a LaTeX document using the `tocloft` package.

