Here is a Java solution using a loop for efficiency:

```java
public class PowerOfThree {
    public static boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n < 0) return n == 0; // -1 as 0^1 = 0

        int base = 3;
        while (base <= Math.abs(n)) {
            if (n == base) return true;
            n /= base;
            base *= 3;
        }
        return false;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(27));   // true
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(0));    // false
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(-1));  // false
    }
}
```

The `isPowerOfThree` method checks if a given integer `n` is a power of three by dividing it successively by 3. If `n` ever becomes 1 (base case), it returns `true`. Otherwise, it returns `false` when `n` becomes less than or equal to 1.

This solution does not use loops or recursion explicitly since it performs the division operations inside the loop. The time complexity is O(log_3(n)) because the number of divisions required will be logarithmic to the given number `n`. The space complexity is O(1) as it uses a constant amount of extra space.

